id,category,user_query,intent,bot_response,tags,confidence_level
1,Attractions & Sightseeing,What are the must-visit places in Kerala?,attractions_general,"Kerala's top attractions include the backwaters of Alleppey (Alappuzha), the tea gardens of Munnar, the wildlife sanctuary at Periyar (Thekkady), the beaches of Varkala and Kovalam, the cultural city of Thrissur, the palace at Padmanabhapuram, and the spice markets of Kochi's Fort area. Each destination offers a unique experience — from houseboat rides to hill treks.",attractions;overview;kerala,high
2,Attractions & Sightseeing,How do I visit the Kerala backwaters?,backwaters_visit,"The best way to experience the Kerala backwaters is from Alleppey (Alappuzha). You can rent a traditional houseboat (kettuvallam) for an overnight stay, or take shorter canoe/shikara rides. Houseboats typically start at ₹6,000–₹15,000 per night depending on the season and amenities. The best months to visit are October to February. Book in advance during peak season (December–January).",backwaters;alleppey;houseboat,high
3,Attractions & Sightseeing,What is there to see in Munnar?,munnar_attractions,"Munnar is famous for its rolling tea plantations, cool climate, and scenic viewpoints. Key spots include Eravikulam National Park (home to the Nilgiri Tahr), Top Station, Mattupetty Dam, Echo Point, Attukal Waterfalls, and the Tea Museum. It's also a great base for trekking. The best time to visit is September to May.",munnar;hill station;tea gardens,high
4,Attractions & Sightseeing,Tell me about Fort Kochi.,fort_kochi,"Fort Kochi is a historic neighbourhood in Kochi city, known for its Chinese fishing nets, colonial-era churches (including the 16th-century St. Francis Church), Dutch Palace (Mattancherry), and vibrant art scene. The Kochi-Muziris Biennale, one of Asia's largest art festivals, is held here. The area is very walkable and best explored on foot or by rented bicycle.",kochi;fort kochi;history;culture,high
5,Attractions & Sightseeing,Is Thekkady worth visiting?,thekkady_visit,"Yes, Thekkady (Periyar) is absolutely worth visiting. The Periyar Tiger Reserve offers boat rides on the lake where you can spot elephants, bison, and various bird species. Activities include bamboo rafting, jungle walks, spice plantation tours, and Kathakali performances in the evening. It's one of the best wildlife experiences in South India.",thekkady;periyar;wildlife;nature,high
6,Attractions & Sightseeing,What are the best beaches in Kerala?,beaches_kerala,"Kerala's best beaches include Varkala (known for cliffs and a laid-back vibe), Kovalam (popular with international tourists, has three coves), Marari (quiet and pristine, great for families), Cherai (near Kochi, good for swimming), and Bekal (near a historic fort in North Kerala). Varkala and Kovalam are the most developed for tourism.",beaches;coastal;kerala,high
7,Attractions & Sightseeing,What can I see in Wayanad?,wayanad_attractions,"Wayanad is a lush green district with tribal heritage and scenic beauty. Must-see spots include Edakkal Caves (prehistoric rock carvings), Chembra Peak (trekking), Soochipara and Meenmutty Waterfalls, Banasura Sagar Dam, and Pookode Lake. It's also known for coffee and pepper plantations. Best visited between October and May.",wayanad;nature;trekking;waterfalls,high
8,Attractions & Sightseeing,Are there any famous temples in Kerala?,temples_kerala,"Kerala has many famous temples. The Padmanabhaswamy Temple in Thiruvananthapuram (one of the wealthiest temples in the world) is a must. Others include Guruvayur Temple (Krishna devotion), Sabarimala (major Ayyappa pilgrimage site), Ettumanoor Shiva Temple, and Thrissur Vadakkunnathan Temple. Note that entry to most temples is restricted to Hindus.",temples;religion;culture,high
9,Attractions & Sightseeing,What is the best time to visit Kerala?,best_time_visit,"The best time to visit Kerala is from October to February when the weather is pleasant and dry. Monsoon season (June–September) is beautiful for those who want lush greenery and Ayurvedic retreats, but heavy rains can disrupt travel plans. March to May is hot and humid. The famous Onam festival (August–September) is a great time to experience Kerala culture.",seasons;weather;travel planning,high
10,Attractions & Sightseeing,Can I see elephants in Kerala?,elephants_kerala,"Yes! Kerala is known as the 'Land of Elephants'. You can see captive temple elephants at Guruvayur (the temple has the second-largest captive elephant population in India), the Elephant Training Centre at Kodanad, or Punnathur Kotta near Guruvayur. In the wild, you can spot elephants at Periyar Tiger Reserve (Thekkady), Wayanad Wildlife Sanctuary, and Silent Valley National Park.",elephants;wildlife;nature,high
11,Food & Restaurants,What is the traditional food of Kerala?,traditional_food,"Kerala cuisine is rich, coconut-based, and full of spices. Must-try dishes include Kerala Sadya (a grand vegetarian feast served on a banana leaf), Appam with Stew, Kerala Fish Curry, Karimeen Pollichathu (pearl spot fish cooked in banana leaf), Puttu and Kadala Curry, Prawn Moilee, Beef Fry, and Kerala Parotta with vegetable or meat curry. Rice is a staple in most meals.",food;cuisine;kerala,high
12,Food & Restaurants,Where should I eat in Kochi?,restaurants_kochi,"In Kochi, try seafood at Malabar Junction or Fort House Restaurant for fine dining with waterfront views. For budget meals, Rice Boat at Taj Malabar is popular for Kerala cuisine. Kayees Biryani in Ernakulam is legendary for Malabar biryani. The street food stalls near Broadway Market and the cafés in Fort Kochi area offer great local snacks at affordable prices.",restaurants;kochi;where to eat,high
13,Food & Restaurants,What is a Kerala Sadya?,sadya_info,"A Kerala Sadya is a traditional vegetarian feast served on a fresh banana leaf, typically during festivals like Onam and Vishu. It includes rice, sambar, rasam, avial (mixed vegetables in coconut), thoran (dry vegetable stir-fry), olan, pachadi, pickles, papadam, and payasam (dessert). It is eaten by hand while seated on the floor. Many restaurants offer Sadya daily or on Sundays.",sadya;festival food;vegetarian,high
14,Food & Restaurants,Is Kerala food very spicy?,food_spice_level,"Kerala food can be quite spicy, especially fish and meat curries which use generous amounts of black pepper, red chilli, and spices. However, vegetarian dishes like avial, olan, and coconut-based preparations are milder. Most restaurants will tone down the spice level if you request it. Appam with stew is a particularly mild and flavourful dish great for those who prefer less spice.",spice;dietary;food preferences,high
15,Food & Restaurants,What is Malabar Biryani?,malabar_biryani,"Malabar Biryani is a fragrant rice dish from the Malabar region (North Kerala), made with short-grain Kaima rice, slow-cooked meat (chicken, mutton, or beef), caramelised onions, and a blend of spices including cardamom, cloves, and saffron. It is lighter and more aromatic than North Indian biryanis. Kozhikode (Calicut) is the best place to try authentic Malabar Biryani.",biryani;north kerala;food,high
16,Food & Restaurants,Are there vegetarian food options in Kerala?,vegetarian_options,"Yes, Kerala has excellent vegetarian options. The traditional Sadya is entirely vegetarian. Restaurants across Kerala serve dishes like Avial, Sambar, Thoran, Olan, Kaalan, and Payasam. Udupi-style South Indian restaurants are widespread and serve dosa, idli, and vada. Sadhya meals are available at Sree Krishna Bhavan and similar vegetarian restaurants in all major cities.",vegetarian;dietary;food,high
17,Food & Restaurants,What seafood should I try in Kerala?,seafood_kerala,"Kerala's coastline means fresh seafood is exceptional. Must-try seafood dishes include Karimeen Pollichathu (pearl spot fish in banana leaf), Prawn Moilee, Kerala Fish Curry with kudampuli (Gamboge), Squid Roast, Crab Masala, Tuna Thoran, and fried sardines. Alleppey and Kochi are the best places for fresh seafood at both budget and fine-dining restaurants.",seafood;food;coastal,high
18,Hotels & Accommodation,What types of accommodation are available in Kerala?,accommodation_types,"Kerala offers a wide range of accommodation — from luxury backwater resorts and heritage hotels to budget homestays and beach guesthouses. Houseboats on the backwaters are a unique stay option. Eco-resorts and tree houses are popular in Wayanad and Munnar. Budget travellers can find good guesthouses from ₹500–₹1,500 per night, while luxury resorts range from ₹8,000 to ₹50,000+.",accommodation;hotels;types,high
19,Hotels & Accommodation,Are homestays a good option in Kerala?,homestays,"Absolutely! Kerala homestays are one of the best ways to experience local culture and food. Many are run by families who offer home-cooked meals and personalised tours. They are available in almost every destination — from backwater villages in Alleppey to tea plantation bungalows in Munnar. Prices range from ₹800 to ₹4,000 per night. Websites like Airbnb and booking.com list many options.",homestay;budget;local experience,high
20,Hotels & Accommodation,What is a houseboat stay like in Kerala?,houseboat_experience,"A Kerala houseboat (kettuvallam) is a traditional wooden boat converted into a floating accommodation with bedrooms, a dining area, and sometimes an open deck. You cruise through the backwaters, enjoy meals cooked on board, and anchor at sunset. Most houseboats have AC and Western toilets. Premium ones have sun decks and glass floors. Alleppey and Kumarakom are the top houseboat destinations.",houseboat;backwaters;accommodation,high
21,Hotels & Accommodation,Which are the best luxury resorts in Kerala?,luxury_resorts,"Kerala's top luxury resorts include Kumarakom Lake Resort, CGH Earth group properties (Coconut Lagoon, Marari Beach, Spice Village), Niraamaya Retreats in Kovalam, Taj Green Cove in Kovalam, and The Leela Kovalam. In Munnar, try Windermere Estate or Fragrant Nature. These resorts offer Ayurvedic treatments, infinity pools, and breathtaking natural settings, typically costing ₹15,000–₹50,000 per night.",luxury;resorts;premium,high
22,Hotels & Accommodation,Where should I stay in Alleppey for the backwaters?,alleppey_accommodation,"In Alleppey, you have three main options: a houseboat stay (overnight cruise on the backwaters), a lakeside resort like Raheem Residency or Emerald Isle Heritage Villa, or a budget guesthouse in town. If you want the authentic backwater experience, book an overnight houseboat. If you prefer a base to explore, a lakeside resort or homestay is ideal. Book well in advance in peak season (December–February).",alleppey;accommodation;backwaters,high
23,Hotels & Accommodation,Are beach resorts available in Kerala?,beach_resorts,"Yes, Kerala has excellent beach resorts particularly in Kovalam and Varkala. In Kovalam, The Leela and Niraamaya Retreats are top-end options. Varkala offers cliff-top boutique hotels and guesthouses ranging from budget to mid-range. Marari Beach near Alleppey has the famous Mararikulam Marari Beach Resort (CGH Earth). Bekal in North Kerala has the Taj Vivanta with stunning views of Bekal Fort.",beach resorts;coastal;accommodation,high
24,Hotels & Accommodation,Can I find budget accommodation in Kerala?,budget_accommodation,"Yes, Kerala has plenty of budget-friendly options. Guest houses and budget hotels in all major tourist areas typically cost ₹500–₹1,500 per night. Hostels in Kochi's Fort area (like Zostel Kochi) cost around ₹350–₹600 per dorm bed. In Varkala, there are many affordable cliff-top guesthouses. Homestays are also budget-friendly and include home-cooked meals.",budget;affordable;accommodation,high
25,Transport & Travel Tips,How do I get to Kerala?,getting_to_kerala,"Kerala has three international airports: Kochi (Cochin International Airport — busiest), Thiruvananthapuram (Trivandrum), and Kozhikode (Calicut). There are direct flights from major Indian cities and international connections from the Middle East, Singapore, and Malaysia. Kerala is also well-connected by train from major Indian cities. The Rajdhani, Duronto, and Jan Shatabdi express trains are popular.",airports;trains;getting there,high
26,Transport & Travel Tips,What is the best way to travel within Kerala?,intra_kerala_transport,"For long distances, Kerala's train network is excellent and scenic. KSRTC buses connect most towns at affordable rates. Within cities, auto-rickshaws and app-based cabs (Ola, Uber) are the most convenient. In tourist spots like Alleppey, renting bicycles is fun. For more flexibility, you can hire a private cab with a driver (typically ₹12–₹18 per km). Ferries connect backwater villages.",transport;getting around;travel,high
27,Transport & Travel Tips,Are ferries available in Kerala?,ferries,"Yes, ferries are an integral part of Kerala's transport system, especially in the backwater regions. KSWTD (Kerala State Water Transport Department) operates ferry services between Alleppey and Kottayam, Ernakulam to Fort Kochi, and other backwater routes. These are affordable and scenic. In Kochi, the ferry between Ernakulam Jetty and Fort Kochi costs just ₹6–₹10 and is a great experience.",ferry;water transport;backwaters,high
28,Transport & Travel Tips,Can I rent a car in Kerala?,car_rental,"Yes, car rentals are available at all major airports and cities in Kerala. Options include self-drive cars (from companies like Zoomcar, Myles, or local agencies) and cars with drivers. For tourists, hiring a car with driver is more practical due to Kerala's hilly terrain and narrow roads. Rates typically range from ₹1,500 to ₹4,000 per day depending on vehicle type and distance.",car rental;transport;self drive,high
29,Transport & Travel Tips,How do auto-rickshaws work in Kerala?,auto_rickshaw,"Auto-rickshaws (autos) are the most common mode of short-distance transport in Kerala. Most autos have meters, but it's advisable to agree on the fare before boarding, especially in tourist areas. Meters start at ₹30 for the first km and charge ₹12–₹15 per additional km. App-based autos (through Rapido or Ola) are also available in major cities and are metered automatically.",auto rickshaw;local transport;tips,high
30,Transport & Travel Tips,How do I travel between Kochi and Alleppey?,kochi_to_alleppey,"Kochi to Alleppey is about 55 km. You can take a KSRTC bus (around 1.5–2 hours, ₹50–₹80), hire a cab (₹700–₹1,000), or drive yourself. There is also a scenic ferry route (KSWTD) which takes longer but offers beautiful backwater views. Trains are not direct — you'd need to change at Ernakulam. Cabs and buses are the most popular options.",kochi;alleppey;route,high
31,Transport & Travel Tips,What should I know about driving in Kerala?,driving_tips,"Driving in Kerala requires caution. Roads in hill stations like Munnar and Wayanad are narrow and winding. Traffic in cities like Kochi can be heavy during peak hours. International tourists need an International Driving Permit. Be alert for pedestrians, cattle, and two-wheelers. During monsoon, landslides can block mountain roads. Google Maps works well but always verify with locals for current conditions.",driving;road trip;safety tips,high
32,Budget & Costs,How much does a trip to Kerala cost?,trip_cost_overview,"A budget trip to Kerala can cost ₹2,000–₹3,500 per person per day (staying in guesthouses, eating at local restaurants, using public transport). A mid-range trip costs ₹4,000–₹8,000 per day (comfortable hotels, occasional cab hire, guided activities). Luxury travel costs ₹15,000–₹50,000+ per day. International flights to Kochi from the Middle East start around ₹8,000–₹20,000 return.",budget;cost;planning,high
33,Budget & Costs,How much does a houseboat cost in Kerala?,houseboat_cost,"A standard AC houseboat in Alleppey costs ₹6,000–₹12,000 per night for two people including meals (breakfast, lunch, and dinner). Premium and deluxe houseboats with more bedrooms and luxury features cost ₹15,000–₹40,000 per night. Prices are higher during peak season (December–January). Day cruises without overnight stay cost ₹2,500–₹5,000.",houseboat;cost;budget,high
34,Budget & Costs,Is Kerala an expensive destination?,kerala_affordability,"Kerala is generally affordable for Indian tourists and budget international travellers. Budget options are widely available — a decent guesthouse costs ₹600–₹1,500 per night, a full meal at a local restaurant costs ₹80–₹200, and bus rides are ₹10–₹100. Luxury options also exist for those who want premium experiences. Compared to European or Southeast Asian beach destinations, Kerala offers excellent value.",affordability;budget;value,high
35,Budget & Costs,How much do Ayurvedic treatments cost in Kerala?,ayurveda_cost,"Ayurvedic treatments vary widely in cost. At authentic Ayurvedic centres certified by Kerala Tourism, a one-hour treatment like Abhyangam starts at ₹800–₹2,000. Full Panchakarma packages (7–21 days) at reputed resorts cost ₹40,000–₹2,00,000 depending on the programme and accommodation. Day-visit packages at wellness centres cost ₹1,500–₹5,000 and include multiple therapies.",ayurveda;wellness;cost,high
36,Budget & Costs,What is the cost of a Kerala to Munnar trip?,munnar_trip_cost,"Kochi to Munnar is about 130 km (3.5–4 hours by road). A one-way taxi costs ₹2,500–₹4,000. KSRTC buses operate daily and cost ₹120–₹200. A 2-night stay in Munnar in a budget hotel costs ₹1,200–₹2,500 per night. For a complete 3-day Munnar trip for two, budget ₹8,000–₹15,000 including travel, accommodation, and activities.",munnar;trip cost;budget,high
37,Budget & Costs,Are there entry fees for Kerala tourist sites?,entry_fees,"Yes, most major attractions have entry fees. Eravikulam National Park in Munnar charges ₹125 (Indian adults) and ₹500 (foreigners). Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary (Thekkady) boat rides cost ₹200–₹450. Padmanabhapuram Palace entry is ₹25 (Indians). Mattancherry Palace (Dutch Palace) in Kochi is free. Most beaches are free. Guided jungle treks at Thekkady cost ₹300–₹1,500 per person.",entry fees;attractions;cost,high
38,Budget & Costs,How much does food cost in Kerala?,food_cost,"Budget eating in Kerala is very affordable. A full meal (rice, curry, and sides) at a local restaurant or Kerala hotel costs ₹60–₹150. A Kerala Sadya at a mid-range restaurant costs ₹200–₹400. Street food like banana fritters and samosas cost ₹10–₹30 each. Fine dining at a resort restaurant can cost ₹1,000–₹3,000 per person. Fresh coconut water from roadside vendors costs ₹20–₹40.",food cost;budget;eating,high
39,Safety & Health Tips,Is Kerala safe for solo travellers?,solo_travel_safety,"Kerala is considered one of the safest states in India for tourists, including solo travellers and women. The state has high literacy rates and a generally respectful culture. Petty theft can occur in crowded areas — keep valuables secure. Avoid isolated areas after dark. Register your accommodation details with the local tourist police if travelling to remote areas. The Kerala Tourism helpline is 1800-425-4747.",safety;solo travel;women,high
40,Safety & Health Tips,What should I do in a medical emergency in Kerala?,medical_emergency,"Kerala has good medical infrastructure. Major hospitals include Amrita Institute of Medical Sciences (Kochi), Medical College Hospital (Thiruvananthapuram), and Calicut Medical College. In an emergency, call 108 (Ambulance — free government service). Most tourist destinations have at least a Primary Health Centre or private clinic nearby. Carry travel insurance that covers medical emergencies.",medical;emergency;healthcare,high
41,Safety & Health Tips,Is the water safe to drink in Kerala?,water_safety,"It is advisable to drink bottled or purified water in Kerala, especially in rural and backwater areas. In cities, hotel rooms typically provide bottled water. Avoid drinking tap water directly. Packaged water bottles (500ml) cost ₹15–₹25 at shops. Most hotels and restaurants use filtered water for cooking and ice, but it's safest to stick to bottled water if you have a sensitive stomach.",water;health;safety,high
42,Safety & Health Tips,Are there any health precautions for visiting Kerala?,health_precautions,"Consult your doctor about vaccinations before visiting India — Typhoid, Hepatitis A, and Tetanus vaccines are commonly recommended. During monsoon (June–September), take precautions against mosquito bites to prevent dengue and malaria — use repellent and wear long sleeves in the evenings. Avoid eating raw street food if you have a sensitive stomach. Carry personal medications and a basic first aid kit.",health;vaccinations;precautions,high
43,Safety & Health Tips,Is Kerala safe during monsoon?,monsoon_safety,"Kerala can be visited during monsoon but requires extra caution. Landslides are a risk in hilly areas like Munnar and Wayanad — always check weather alerts before travel. Some backwater routes may be disrupted by heavy rains. Sea swimming is not advisable during the monsoon due to strong currents and rough waters. On the positive side, the landscape is lush, prices are lower, and crowds are fewer.",monsoon;safety;weather,high
44,Safety & Health Tips,What emergency numbers should I know in Kerala?,emergency_numbers,"Key emergency numbers in Kerala: Police — 100, Ambulance — 108, Fire — 101, Women's Helpline — 1091, Tourist Helpline (Kerala Tourism) — 1800-425-4747 (toll-free), Coast Guard (for sea emergencies) — 1554. The national emergency number 112 connects to all emergency services. Save these in your phone before your trip.",emergency;contact numbers;safety,high
45,Safety & Health Tips,Are there any wildlife safety tips for Kerala?,wildlife_safety,"When visiting wildlife sanctuaries like Periyar or Wayanad, always follow guide instructions. Do not venture off designated trails. Maintain a safe distance from elephants and bison — they can be aggressive if startled. Do not feed wildlife. In forest areas, tuck in your pants and wear closed shoes to protect against leeches and snakes. Never approach or feed elephants in the wild.",wildlife;safety;nature,high
46,Attractions & Sightseeing,What cultural experiences can I have in Kerala?,cultural_experiences,"Kerala is rich in cultural traditions. Watch a Kathakali dance performance (classical dance-drama with elaborate costumes and makeup) in Kochi or Thekkady. Attend a Kalaripayattu martial arts demonstration. Experience Mohiniyattam (classical dance) and Theyyam ritual performances in North Kerala. During Onam (August–September), witness boat races, floral carpet decorations (Pookalam), and traditional celebrations.",culture;dance;performance,high
47,Attractions & Sightseeing,What is the Kochi-Muziris Biennale?,kochi_biennale,"The Kochi-Muziris Biennale is one of Asia's largest and most prestigious contemporary art festivals, held every two years in Fort Kochi (Kochi) from December to March. It features international and Indian artists showcasing installations, paintings, sculptures, and multimedia works across heritage venues in Fort Kochi. The next edition typically starts in December. Entry is free or at a nominal fee.",art;biennale;kochi;culture,high
48,Attractions & Sightseeing,Can I do trekking in Kerala?,trekking,"Kerala offers excellent trekking opportunities. Popular treks include Chembra Peak in Wayanad (the tallest peak in Wayanad, with a heart-shaped lake), Agasthyarkoodam in Thiruvananthapuram (restricted access), Meesapulimala near Munnar (the second-highest peak in Kerala), and the trails in Periyar Tiger Reserve. Most treks require prior permission and a licensed guide. Best trekking season is October to April.",trekking;adventure;nature,high
49,Food & Restaurants,What is Kerala's famous breakfast?,kerala_breakfast,"Kerala's most iconic breakfast dishes include Puttu (steamed rice cake served with Kadala curry or banana), Idiyappam (rice noodles served with coconut milk and egg curry), Appam with vegetable stew or coconut milk, and Dosa/Idli with sambar and chutney. Tapioca (Kappa) with fish curry is also a popular morning meal in coastal areas. Most local restaurants and homestays serve these by 7–9 AM.",breakfast;food;cuisine,high
50,Transport & Travel Tips,What is the best route for a 7-day Kerala itinerary?,seven_day_itinerary,"A popular 7-day Kerala itinerary: Days 1–2: Kochi (Fort Kochi, Mattancherry, Kathakali show). Day 3: Drive to Munnar (tea gardens, Eravikulam NP). Day 4: Munnar to Thekkady (Periyar boat ride, spice tour). Day 5: Thekkady to Alleppey (houseboat overnight stay). Day 6: Alleppey to Varkala (beach, cliff walk). Day 7: Varkala to Thiruvananthapuram (Padmanabhaswamy Temple, departure).",itinerary;planning;travel route,high
51,Attractions & Sightseeing,Who is the Kerala Tourism Minister?,tourism_minister,"The current Minister for Tourism in Kerala is P. C. Vishnunadh, who was appointed in May 2026. He succeeds the past minister P. A. Mohammed Riyas.","minister, tourism minister, government, satheesan cabinet",high
52,Attractions & Sightseeing,Who is the current Minister for Tourism in Kerala?,tourism_minister,"The current Minister for Tourism in Kerala is P. C. Vishnunadh, who was appointed in May 2026. He succeeds the past minister P. A. Mohammed Riyas.","minister, tourism minister, government, satheesan cabinet",high
